[Malignant catarrhal fever (MCF) is a generalized, often fatal disease caused by a herpesvirus that infects a variety of ruminants. The clinical course of the disease in individual animals is very varied and it may be peracute, acute, chronic, or mild. In the acute form of the disease, the clinical signs are usually severe inflammation of the mucosae of the respiratory and alimentary tracts and conjunctivae, as well as eyes and skin. The lesions are accompanied by mucopurulent discharge.

MCF is caused by 3 herpesvirus strains, alcelaphine herpesvirus 1 of wildebeests, ovine herpesvirus 2 of domestic sheep, and MCFV-WTD of goats. Neither of these viruses cause clinical disease in their natural hosts. - Mod.PMB


A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2578983,205.]
